<li id="cite_note-65"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-65">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFKoehler2011" class="citation web cs1">Koehler, Robert (10 May 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/68558939@N00/5707195482/">"Bodhisattva of Mercy, Gilsangsa Temple"</a>. <i>Flickr.com</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">27 November</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Flickr.com&amp;rft.atitle=Bodhisattva+of+Mercy%2C+Gilsangsa+Temple&amp;rft.date=2011-05-10&amp;rft.aulast=Koehler&amp;rft.aufirst=Robert&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.flickr.com%2Fphotos%2F68558939%40N00%2F5707195482%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGuanyin" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-66"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-66">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation audio-visual cs1 cs1-prop-script cs1-prop-foreign-lang-source"> <bdi lang="zh">不肯去观音</bdi> &#91;<i>Avalokitesvara</i>&#93; (in Chinese). 2013. <q>In the first five minutes, there are two chantings of the Heart Sutra.  The first time, Buddhist monks chant in Chinese blessing the making of a statue of Avalokitesvara bodhisattva for the benefit of a disabled prince. (The prince is later healed and becomes the future <a href="/wiki/Emperor_Xu%C4%81nzong" class="mw-redirect" title="Emperor Xuānzong">Emperor Xuānzong</a>.) The second time, we hear the singing of the mantra of the Sanskrit Heart Sutra in the background. Shortly after the <a href="/wiki/N%C4%ABlaka%E1%B9%87%E1%B9%ADha_Dh%C4%81ra%E1%B9%87%C4%AB" title="Nīlakaṇṭha Dhāraṇī">Nīlakaṇṭha Dhāraṇī</a> is chanted.  The Chinese version of the <a href="/wiki/Eleven-Faced_Avalokitesvara_Heart_Dharani_Sutra#The_Heart-dhāraṇī_of_Avalokiteśvara-ekadaśamukha" title="Eleven-Faced Avalokitesvara Heart Dharani Sutra">Eleven-Faced Guanyin Heart Dharani</a> is also chanted. Egaku chants the Heart Sutra in Japanese in a later segment. The film is a loose retelling of the origin of Mount Putuo.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=%E4%B8%8D%E8%82%AF%E5%8E%BB%E8%A7%82%E9%9F%B3&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGuanyin" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
